jobDescription:
James practices primarily in commercial law, with a focus on technical, engineering and construction disputes, equity and class actions.

Before joining the Bar, James was an Associate at Allens for three years in the construction disputes and commercial litigation teams. His practice included advising construction and engineering clients on complex construction and technical disputes and the administration of major projects. James was also involved in complex class actions, insurance disputes and product liability claims.

Prior to his legal career, James worked as an engineer in both construction and consulting environments. James was involved in the construction of a major arterial transport link and consulted in relation to the design, installation and commissioning of a diverse range of bespoke robotics in various industrial settings.

James read with Simon T Pitt and his senior mentor is Jeremy Twigg QC.

James's profile is available here: http://www.deverslist.com.au/devers-list/waters-james

description:
Fiona is the Chairman of Allens. She advises clients in complex merger clearances, access matters, cartel and other antitrust investigations and litigation. Fiona is often called on to assist companies formulate regulatory strategies where the ACCC is a key stakeholder.

She has been involved in the largest and most complex merger clearances in Australia, including working with international counsel and economists on global mergers. Fiona has acted in high-profile competition cases, including proceedings that established the application of legal professional privilege to investigations brought by the competition regulator, proceedings alleging collusive conduct by major retail chains, the land and submarine cable cartel and seminal misuse of market power cases.

Fiona is Chair of the Competition and Consumer Committee of the Law Council of Australia and is an active speaker on regulatory and competition issues. Fiona is recognised as a leading competition practitioner in Chambers Asia-Pacific, Best Lawyers and Global Competition Review.

I am an Associate in the International Arbitration Group and the Asia-Pacific Public International Law and Investor-State Dispute Settlement practice at Clifford Chance in Perth. 

I act for clients primarily in the energy and resources sectors, having worked on disputes arising out of major gold, iron ore, oil and LNG projects in Africa, Australia and South East Asia. My recent work includes acting in complex arbitrations under the UNCITRAL, ICC and SIAC Rules.

I graduated from Murdoch University in 2013 with a Bachelor of Laws with Distinction and a Bachelor of Arts majoring in Psychology. I was admitted as a lawyer of the Supreme Court of Western Australia and as a barrister and solicitor of the High Court of Australia in November 2014.
jobDescription:
I am an Associate in the firm's International Arbitration Group and Asia-Pacific Public International Law and Investor-State Dispute Settlement practice. I have experience predominantly in investor-state and infrastructure arbitration matters.

Some of my recent experience includes acting for:
- Kingsgate Consolidated Ltd in a bet-the-company arbitration against the Kingdom of Thailand pursuant to the UNCITRAL Rules (Singapore-seated) under the Thailand-Australia Free Trade Agreement concerning claims over the expropriation of a gold mine in northern Thailand
- Saipem SA in UNCITRAL and ICC rules arbitrations (Perth-seated and Singapore-seated, respectively) concerning claims under a contract for the construction of a jetty for a major offshore LNG project in Australia
- a European energy company in a dispute with an African Government under a Production Sharing Agreement for an offshore gas field, and
- a global insulation contractor in relation to various disputes arising out of an insulation sub-contract concerning the construction of a major LNG project in Western Australia.

- acting for Energy Drilling Australia Pty Ltd, a subsidiary of Ausdrill Ltd, in relation to trial proceedings in the South Australian Supreme Court, arising out of the termination of a drilling services agreement.

jobDescription:
I commenced at Jackson McDonald as a law graduate in March 2016. During my first year at Jackson McDonald I rotated in the Workplace Relations and Safety team. I experienced and participated in a range of work including conducting legal research, drafting employment contracts and working with other team members to establish precedents and internal research databases. 

I also completed an 8 week rotation in Jackson McDonald's Legal Technology Support team that assists other teams in the firm in document management, particularly in large scale litigation discovery. My time spent in this team was invaluable, as I was exposed to a wide range of technologies and databases and I was encouraged to develop my project management skills. I also learnt the importance of delivering good instructions to others when delegating work. 

Admitted on 16 December 2016, I am now a Solicitor in Jackson McDonald's Dispute Resolution and Litigation team. 

Since arriving in the team in January 2017, I have worked on 3 large commercial litigation matters relating to contract disputes, intellectual property and construction. I also enjoy assisting in pro bono litigation matters and assist in Legal Aid's community legal education program 'R U Legal?'. In 2016, I also undertook a secondment at the Street Law Centre in East Perth. 

I am a keen member of Jackson McDonald's Branching Out Committee which assists junior professionals to develop their business development and networking skills and provides them with opportunities to put those skills into practice.

Blake has considerable experience working in the Resources, Energy and Projects, Real Estate, and Government sectors, having worked in back-end matters, ranging from large-scale court proceedings, through to bespoke alternative dispute resolution options for small-sized claims, for both private and government clients. 

As well as back-end matters, Blake has also advised clients on general risk advisory on large scale projects, and the management of significant or sensitive issues on current projects (contentious and non-contentious), through advising teams on-site, attending meetings, drafting correspondence, preparing risk analysis models and liaising directly with counterparties to resolve litigious issues during project delivery. 

Blake has a strong understanding of procurement models, including traditional models such as; construct only, D&C, EPCM, O&M and alliancing.  Blake regularly assists clients when drafting, reviewing and negotiating all project documentation, and is equipped to manage projects from inception, through delivery and to close out.

During his career, Blake has also gained significant experience, both on the east and west coast, drafting and managing the conduct of disputes in the form of ICC Arbitration, expert determination, Supreme Court litigation and security of payment adjudication.

description:
Stephanie Puris is a solicitor in the Dispute Resolution team in the Perth office where she specialises in commercial litigation and insolvency. She has experience in the areas of contractual and corporate disputes, corporate restructures, intellectual property and trade practices. Her clients span the financial services, telecommunications, manufacturing and resources sectors.

Stephanie is also involved in a wide range of pro bono work, and is the probono coordinator for the Perth KWM in the Community program. 

Stephanie undertook a 6-month secondment to the National Children’s and Youth Law Centre (NCYLC) in 2011 and has maintained her involvement with the Centre by becoming the national key contact for NCYLC within KWM.  Through this relationship Stephanie has had significant experience in providing legal assistance to children and young people.  Since 2012, she has coordinated a national partnership between King & Wood Mallesons, ASIC, Telstra and NCYLC to provide children and young people with online legal advice.

Stephanie is the KWM representative on the national steering committee of the Child Rights Taskforce and has been actively involved in the work of the Taskforce, including drafting various submissions to the United Nations on Australia’s compliance with its international obligations.
